I first encountered Khyesha when she was a student in my class at White's Creek High school in 2013.
https://dzhhw2kso6jlo.cloudfront.net/chart-images/v1/belmont-university/student-life/diversity/chart-ethnic-diversity_xl.png
Khy was one of a small handful of students who recieved the "Bridges to Belmont" scholarship from Whites Creek High School.
http://www.belmont.edu/adult-degree/_images/Belmont_University.jpg

Khyesha was from a family whose mother sturggled to move them out of the projects so that her kids would grow up in a better environment. During the time that I knew her well enough for her to tell me, she lived in north Nashville, Madison, and in East Nashville, sometimes just staying with friends of her mother's. Khyesha became a master of public transportation and always got herself to and from school not only on time, but with enough time built in to visit teachers for extra projects and extracurriculars.
She was a natural leader in my class who was interested in learning everything.
Whites Creek High School does not have a stellar reputation amongst the schools of MNPS. Some of its bad rap is exageration, but here are some facts.
https://images2.publicschoolreview.com/charts/74000/74750/Whites-Creek-High-School-School-Ethnicity-id74750.png

70% of students at WCHS are eligible for free/reduced lunch. (The district average is 65% while the state average is 49%) -- this is a north Nashville school where many of the families served are dealing with financial issues.
Whites Creek student demographics are not super diverse -  mostly Black (79%), some White, and a touch Hispanic.
Belmont University, by contrast to White's Creek, is almost 80% White, a total reversal of the makeup of the color spectrum of faces Khyesha was used to seeing.

I met with her a few times during her freshman year and she expressed that the school was very supportive once she and her peers (those in situations similar to hers) made clear how detrimental it was even for her to go 'home' for the summer break -- this was not something people in more privelidged circumstances had really thought about.
Khyesha remained on the Dean's List for all of her years at Belmont so far.
She was salutatorian of her graduating class, and gave her speech in Belmont's auditorium.
https://news.belmont.edu/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/1.png

She also expressed uncertainty that she would be able to keep up with the level of academic work that her classmates seemed prepared for; I knew that while her high school experience had not prepared her perfectly for high level academics, she had persevered through much more and could do it, if it was the right thing for her.
What impresses me most about the Khyesha I know is how deep of a thinker she is -- she was showing a depth of awareness I had barely begun to grasp in my late 20s when she was just 18.
